With 270 confirmed cases and nearly a 10 percent fatality rate, senior officials including the vice president and the Vice Minister of Health have confirmed infections... just as they have played a role in Middle Eastern politics in the COVID-19 epidemic, iran is once again the eye of the storm.

Iran's influence on its neighbours is also ill timed to reflect the spread of the disease: confirmed cases from Iraq, Lebanon, Afghanistan, Bahrain and Kuwait have all travelled to Iran.

The World Health Organization has singled out Iran as a particular concern for countries with a sudden increase in cases. A World Health Organization team will travel to Iran over the weekend to help contain the outbreak.

However, compared with neighbouring countries, Iran's health system is "well-matched" : it has a tiered health care system that primary health care 95 per cent of the rural population and is rated "excellent" by UNICEF. Even some Afghan and Iraqi refugees who have sought refuge in Iran have access to health insurance.

Iran is also a popular medical tourist destination throughout the Middle East. About 600,000 tourists travelled to Iran for treatment or cosmetic surgery between March and July last year because of low prices and better medical technology.

Still, the impact on Iran's health care system is clear. Although 97 per cent of the medicines used in Iran are produced domestically, one third of the raw materials are imported; most medical equipment is totally dependent on imports.

In the face of the surge in new crown disease, officials of the Iranian Federation of Importers of Medical Equipment admitted that US sanctions had affected the import of new crown virus test kits. Local Chinese in Tehran told interface news that masks and disinfectant had been snapped up.

###"incredible work. "

The Bloomberg L.P. regularly ranks economies on the efficiency of health care, based on indicators such as life expectancy, the absolute cost of health care, and the cost of health care relative to average income.

Iran ranked 39th in the index in 2018, with a life expectancy of 75.7 years. The United States is ranked 54th and second to last in terms of high health care costs.

The non-governmental Organization, the Johns Hopkins University and the Economist Intelligence Unit published the Global Health Security Index in 2019, ranking the health security capabilities of 195 countries.

In total, Iran ranked 97th, ahead of neighboring Iraq, Syria, Azerbaijan, Turkmenistan, Afghanistan and Pakistan. Iran ranks 62nd, well above average, even ahead of South Africa, Vietnam and Qatar, in the "adequate and robust health system to treat patients and protect health workers" index.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Red is for preparing the weakest country, Khaki is for preparing the better country, light yellow is for preparing the best country.

After the Islamic Revolution in 1979, Iran began to set up the public health system, has undergone four major reforms.

At present, health affairs in Iran are managed by the Iranian Ministry of Health and Medical Education. On top of the Ministry of Health and Health Education there are two cross-sectoral committees, one responsible for cross-sectoral cooperation and health decision-making and the other for the development of health insurance schemes.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Image Credit: screenshot

Unlike many countries, medical services and education in Iran are under the jurisdiction of the Ministry of Health and Medical Education. Each province has at least one medical college, whose president is also the local health officer, who reports to the Ministry of Health and Medical Education. There are currently 67 medical schools in Iran's 31 provinces.

Under the Ministry of Health and Medical Education, the boards of directors of the provincial medical schools also serve as the second level of management, while the hospitals of the medical schools provide targeted medical services to residents of large cities.

Under the medical school for the regional health network. The regional health network is responsible for the management of regional health centers, regional public hospitals, special clinics and other institutions. Under the regional health centres there are rural and urban health services.

Rural Health services are mainly represented by Health houses, which are also the first places for patients to visit in rural areas. In general, medical rooms are equipped with commonly used drugs, medical equipment, and one male and one female community medical staff. Known as Behvarzes, these community health workers have received two years of professional training in vaccines, maternal and child health care, and basic health care.

By 2019, more than 18,000 health-care homes and 32,000 community health workers had been set up in rural areas, covering 95 per cent of the rural population. Patients who can not be handled by the health houses are referred to the rural health centres and those who can not be handled by the rural health centres to the regional health centres.

Similar networks have been established in cities, including Health posts and urban Health centres. This is the system that Iran has always been proud of, the primary health care system, known as the "incredible masterpiece. ".

The system was set up in 1985 during the iran-iraq war. In addition to providing free basic health care to rural residents, it has also helped Iran to reduce infant and maternal mortality rates significantly.

More than 74 per cent of Iran's population of about 80m now lives in urban areas. Compared with rural areas, the primary health care system in urban areas has not achieved good results, and the mechanism of patient-by-patient transfer has not been effectively implemented. But the city's health care resources are more concentrated, most public hospitals and almost all private hospitals are located in urban areas.

There are three main categories of medical institutions in Iran: public, private and NGO. Public hospitals are responsible for medical services from the primary level to the tertiary level, i.e. the medical school level, while private institutions are mainly responsible for outpatient services in urban areas, while ngos provide specialized services for individual diseases such as childhood cancer and diabetes.

Departments and agencies such as the Ministry of Defence, the Ministry of Oil, the Army of the Guardians of the Islamic Revolution, the Social Security Organization (SSO) that provides social security services, and their own hospitals. By 2018, Iran had 1,117 hospitals, 130,000 beds and 400,000 medical personnel. Eighty percent of these beds are owned by public hospitals.

In health insurance, more than 60% of the population had no health insurance until 1994. But today, people with different professional backgrounds have different health care systems.

Independently run social security organizations (SSO) are the most commonly used system, consisting mainly of pension and health insurance, from which 52 per cent of the Iranian population currently benefits.

The Social Security Organization's health insurance system mainly targets non-governmental sector employees, self-employed persons and their families, and the premiums are shared by employees, employers and the government. Insured persons receive free medical care when they visit a medical institution under the Social Security Organization, with partial reimbursement from other hospitals and clinics. At its peak, public hospitals can claim between 85% and 90% of their inpatient costs.

Government workers and students, military personnel and their families, and rural residents have different health insurance plans. In 2014, President Rohani launched the Rouhani health plan to cover people without any insurance. By 2017, the program will reach nearly 11 million people.

Although coverage has expanded, Iran's health care plan has also been criticized for its complexity and uneven government spending.

Iran's total health spending in 2016 was $36 billion, or 8.1 percent of GDP, according to the World Bank. The more developed economies of Japan were 10.93 per cent, Israel 7.31 per cent, Saudi Arabia 5.74 per cent and the United Arab Emirates 3.52 per cent.

Total health costs are high as a share of GDP, with out-of-pocket payments accounting for 35.5 per cent, although much of this is funded by the government budget and health insurance.

###Hot spot for medical tourism

In the field of medical research and innovation, the 2019 Global Innovation Index: Creating a healthy life as a future of medical innovation, published by Cornell University, Insead and WIPO, reveals that, iran ranks 61st out of nearly 130 economies, ahead of Saudi Arabia and Qatar.

Iran has adopted a national drug policy based on generic drugs since 1979. By 2018,97 percent of the drugs used in Iran are made locally, with a market value of about $4.5 billion. There are currently 186 indigenous pharmaceutical companies and 232 pharmaceutical import companies in Iran.

Up to 92% of the population uses medicare when buying medicines. In order to control the price of drugs, the government has implemented a subsidy policy for the production and import of many kinds of drugs. By 2017, life expectancy for Iranian men had risen from 67.7 years in 1984 to 75.47 years, and for women from 71 to 79.36 years.

With better medical conditions and technology, Iran has become a popular destination for medical tourists in Iraq, Syria, Afghanistan, Azerbaijan, Armenia and other countries. Tourists usually go to Iran for plastic surgery, heart surgery, Orthopedic Surgery, infertility treatment and so on.

Medical tourism has also become one of Iran's emerging industries. Currently, more than 400 hospitals in Iran are involved in medical tourism, of which 170 have been granted permission to set up international patient zones. To facilitate medical tourists from other countries, Iran has signed cooperation agreements with 13 neighboring countries. In addition, Iran has also set up a number of private tourism companies, specifically to arrange medical travel to Iran.

The resumption of US sanctions has dealt a severe blow to Iran's economy, but it has also opened up more business opportunities for medical tourism.

Thanks to the devaluation of the Iranian rial caused by the sanctions, Iran attracted more than 600,000 medical tourists in the four months from March to July last year, the same number as in the past year.

According to Ariamedtour, an Iranian medical travel company, Iran ranks among the top 10 countries in orthopaedic surgery technology, while knee replacement surgery costs an average of $2,800. Knee replacement surgery in South Africa costs between $13,000 and $15,000.

Iranian authorities estimate that each medical tourist spends between $3,600 and $7,600 in Iran. In 2018, medical tourism generated $1.2 billion in revenue. Under Iran's sixth economic development plan (2017-2022) , the government plans to attract between 500,000 and 600,000 medical tourists a year.

###Under sanctions

Despite the region's top configuration, years of international sanctions had already hit Iran's health care system long before the nuclear deal was reached.

In November 2017, members of Iran's parliament sent a letter to Rohani calling on the government to repay the Social Security Organization, the main health care provider, within 10 years. With interest, the government is expected to repay more than $36 billion.

At the end of the same year, Iran was hit by two large-scale earthquakes. In an interview after the earthquake, an official from the Ministry of Health and Medical Education pointed out that 70 percent of hospitals in Iran were built 50 years ago, and many were in poor repair and in urgent need of regular maintenance.

Iran's deputy health minister, Iraj Harirchi, who confirmed the infection in the latest outbreak, also wrote in the Lancet last August that before the nuclear deal, nearly six million Non-communicable disease patients in Iran have been unable to get the treatment they need because of international sanctions.

Iran's medicine and medical equipment have taken a bigger hit since the resumption of US sanctions.

Although 97 per cent of medicines in Iran are manufactured locally, one third of the raw materials needed to produce medicines are imported. Essential medicines for the treatment of rare diseases, chronic diseases, multiple cancers, blood diseases and the like are entirely dependent on imports.

In medical devices, Iran is more dependent on imports.

According to the Iranian National Medical Device Authority, the Iranian medical device market was worth $2.5 billion in 2018, but only 30 percent of the devices were made in Iran, and the remaining 70 percent were imported, basic equipment includes magnetic resonance Imagin, scanning equipment, orthopaedic equipment, and even hospital beds.

A month before the US formally announced its withdrawal from the nuclear deal in May 2018, Iran's central bank began preparations to subsidize the exchange rate for Iranian companies to import government-specified necessities. The list of essentials released at the time included more than 5,000 drugs and more than 22,000 medical devices.

Although the government is prepared, there are still many medicines and medical devices that are not subsidized. In the case of Dentistry, the Health Committee of the Iranian parliament announced that only 392 of the more than 2,000 imported dental products and devices used in Iran were eligible for subsidized exchange rates.

A private dentist in Tehran told Human Rights Watch that many of the medical devices used in his hospitals are not subsidized by the exchange rate, and that as the Iranian rial depreciates, the cost of importing equipment rises, hospitals will be unable to buy new equipment and will have to use old equipment.

Although United States sanctions exempt humanitarian goods such as essential medicines and medical equipment, banks and financial institutions in many countries are reluctant to deal with Iranian companies in the face of the risk of United States secondary sanctions.

The report by Human Rights Watch cites the experience of a British lawyer. The lawyer pointed out that as long as his client wanted to do business with Iranian companies, he needed to be prepared to go to court, even if it involved humanitarian goods such as medicines.

In the course of a transaction, it is often the bank that refuses to transfer the funds. Even with the threat of a lawsuit against the bank, and the bank eventually transferring the money, the lawyer would have to go through the pre-trial process. The process is time-consuming and sometimes customers simply choose not to do business with Iranian companies.

According to EU trade data released by the European Commission in 2019, the EU exported $920m worth of drugs to Iran in 2016, a year after the nuclear deal; by 2018 that figure had fallen to $795m.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
In addition to making it harder for patients who need them to be treated, the decline in imports has also led to higher drug prices.

Parviz Sadeghi, a diabetic, described the difficult process of buying insulin in Tehran in an interview with AFP this week.

Currently unemployed, Sadji has been suffering from diabetes for nearly 10 years. He used to be able to go to any pharmacy to buy insulin, but now he has to move around and ends up waiting in line for hours at a pharmacy to get the insulin he needs for treatment.

Three years ago, insulin cost about $1.10. Today, the price has tripled, according to Sadji. But despite the job losses, SADJI's insulin bills are still fully covered by Medicare.

Local Chinese in Teheran, Ah Hua, told interface news in an interview that he could already feel the shortage of medical institutions when he went to see a doctor. Many specialty drugs can not be produced locally, leading to a shortage of needed drugs, as well as outdated hospital equipment, some of which are not even available, according to Hua's experience.

With the outbreak of the new crown, the impact of sanctions on Iran's medical equipment has been further amplified. To add insult to injury, Iran was blacklisted by the International Financial Action Task Force on 21 February. Blacklisting would subject all transactions with Iran to greater scrutiny.

Iranian Medical Equipment Importers Union Vice President Farad (Ramin Fallah)24, told Iranian media interviews complained that the United States sanctions and blacklist incident has affected the import of new coronavirus test kits.

Farah revealed that a number of foreign companies were ready to ship the kits to Iran, but because foreign banks refused to deal with Iranian companies, Iran can not make bank transfers.

So far, only the World Health Organization have circumvented sanctions by sending four ships of testing equipment and medical staff protection equipment to Iran. China donated 250,000 masks and 5,000 nucleic acid test kits to Iran.

Farad also pointed out that the most important medical equipment in response to the new crown epidemic is ICU equipment and breathing machines. He did not disclose the number of ICU equipment available in Iran, saying only that the number of breathing machines was "sufficient" .

In preparation for the outbreak, he will travel to Turkey, "human meat Daigou" , with cash to buy 2M medical masks, and then shipped back from Turkey to Iran.

###"reporting is the most prominent issue. "

In addition to the impact of sanctions on hardware, Iran has a complete medical system and better medical technology, but its infectious disease surveillance system still has many problems.

Like many countries, Iran has an infectious disease prevention and Control Department: The Center for Infectious Disease Control (CCDC) under the Ministry of Health and Medical Education.

However, an article by Abbas Norouzinejad of the Center for Infectious Disease Control and prevention and a number of Iranian scholars published in the Iranian Medical Journal in July 2019 pointed out that there were many problems in Iran's system for the prevention and control of infectious diseases, these include the failure to report the disease when it is discovered, the lack of knowledge of the infectious disease by medical staff, and the ineffective intervention after the discovery of the disease.

The article points out that reporting is one of the most prominent problems, with many private doctors failing to report infectious disease to regulators when they find it. This is partly because of a lack of incentives, but also because many private health-care providers do not understand the reporting system.

In the government's primary health care, manual registration is still used in some urban and rural health centres. Only 25 per cent of the 60 urban and rural health centres surveyed used computer records to collect and process data.

In terms of intervention measures, due to the limited number of beds reserved by hospitals for public health emergencies, the lack of specialized doctors in some first-line hospitals and financial problems, the hardware conditions for intervention are not ideal, cross-sectoral support and coordination is also lacking.

Faced with limited hardware and software conditions, the Iranian government, in its response to the new outbreak, said on the one hand that the epidemic could not be more dangerous than the flu, and on the other hand, it took measures with reservations, this includes closing schools, educational institutions, cinemas and exhibition halls in many places and sterilising public transport in many places.

Many Western medical experts have speculated that Iran's initially staggering confirmed patient mortality was largely due to the fact that patients with less severe symptoms were not detected. On the one hand, it may be due to inadequate testing methods, reporting is not timely, it may also be due to the aging of medical equipment inaccurate. The actual number of cases should be much higher than the current number of reported cases, as mild cases are not detected in time.

According to Hua, local people in Tehran have different reactions to the epidemic, people on the streets wearing and not wearing masks have. Some people continued to party without masks, while others began to travel to other countries.

But compared with the outbreak of the first few days, the attention of the public has significantly increased, disinfectant and masks have been snapped up. Religious Services at Tehran's mosques have been canceled, and some neighborhoods have begun handing out free masks to high-risk people. "I haven't received them myself, but the vegetable sellers downstairs have. ".

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The military makes masks. Image: Twitter

On Saturday, Iran's Ministry of Health and Medical Education announced it would distribute free masks and disinfectant to government medical institutions. In the Shiite holy city of Qom, where the outbreak occurred, authorities will distribute face masks and disinfectant from door to door.

The Ministry of Health and Medical Education requires all mask manufacturers in the country to hand over at least 50 per cent of the daily production of masks to the Ministry of Health in exchange for cash.

Reza Rahmani, Iran's Minister of Industry, mines and trade, has announced that 13 of the country's leading mask makers will start work 24 hours a day to produce about two million masks.

Iran's nanotechnology headquarters signed an agreement with the Ministry of Health and two enterprises on the 26th to produce 15 million N94 and N99 nanometer masks. Production of face masks and disinfectants has also begun, and all medical facilities in the Army of the Guardians of the Islamic Revolution will be involved in the prevention and control of the epidemic. At the same time, the Iranian government also asked the Iranian central bank to prepare foreign currency for priority imports of face masks.

Despite a series of measures, the number of confirmed cases in Iran is still rising sharply. Rohani has said the government has no plans to close the city or town. For Iran, which is under sanctions and blacklisted, the economic impact of such a move would no doubt be even greater.

Hua is concerned that there are not enough beds in designated hospitals set up by the government to treat confirmed patients. The number of beds per 1,000 population was just 1.72 in 2017, according to Iran's Ministry of Health.

As a precaution, HWA plans to stay at home for the next few weeks as much as possible, "and the community store will take care of that. ".
